      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented test suite, issue tracking, and change-control procedures commensurate with MRL 5.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022R2) is deployed under a validated software configuration management plan. A regression test suite of 47 canonical cases is executed on each release; results are archived in the team's quality management system. Change-control records and a software validation report conforming to IEC 62304 Class B are on file. SQA level 3 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Demonstrated order-of-accuracy convergence on manufactured solutions relevant to rotating-frame turbulent flow.",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) studies confirm second-order spatial accuracy for the incompressible RANS solver in rotating reference frames. Convergence exponents of 1.94–2.07 were measured across three mesh refinement levels. Results are consistent with published FDA round-robin code-verification findings."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) reported for all QoIs; discretization error bounded to less than 5% of hemolysis index at all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study (6.2 M, 14.8 M, 31.5 M cells) performed at all five flow-speed combinations. Richardson-extrapolated GCI values for hemolysis index range from 1.8% to 4.3%, within the 5% acceptance bound. Wall y+ distributions confirm near-wall resolution requirements for the SST k-omega model are satisfied across all operating points."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions documented with measurement uncertainty; flow rates and rotational speeds match simulation inputs within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA bench test conditions are fully documented in the NHLBI dataset release. Flow rates are controlled to ±0.05 L/min and rotational speed to ±5 RPM. Fluid temperature, viscosity, and hematocrit are reported with calibration traceability. Boundary condition uncertainty is propagated through the Monte Carlo UQ ensemble."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative agreement metrics (e.g., NRMSE, E_rel) reported with uncertainty; systematic bias less than 15% for hemolysis index across all operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted hemolysis index values agree with bench measurements within 9–14% across all five operating points when both simulation and experimental uncertainties are accounted for. NRMSE of 0.11 is within acceptance. Velocity field comparisons against PIV data show area-averaged errors below 8% in the impeller region. Validation uncertainty analysis follows the ASME V&V 20 framework."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation directly correspond to the hemolysis index metric required for the COU decision.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI — normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) — is identical between the validation experiments and the COU prediction task. Secondary QoIs (velocity magnitude in impeller passage, shear stress distribution) are validated as surrogates that underpin the hemolysis power-law model. No surrogate substitution is required for the primary decision metric."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments performed on the same device geometry, fluid, and operating envelope as the COU; no extrapolation beyond validated range.",
      "rationale": "All five COU operating points fall within the envelope of the FDA NHLBI validation dataset (2–8 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). The test fluid (bovine blood at 33% hematocrit) is representative of clinical VAD conditions. Geometry is the FDA generic centrifugal pump — identical to the simulation domain. No extrapolation is required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated; residuals reduced by at least four orders of magnitude and monitored QoIs stabilized to less than 0.1% change over final 500 iterations.",
      "rationale": "All simulations achieve six-order-of-magnitude reduction in mass and momentum residuals. Hemolysis index monitors show cycle-to-cycle variation below 0.05% over the final 1000 iterations. Pseudo-transient continuation was used to improve convergence robustness at off-design operating points."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by an independent analyst; documented checklist covering boundary conditions, material properties, solver settings, and post-processing scripts.",
      "rationale": "An independent senior CFD engineer performed a blind setup review against a 74-item simulation checklist prior to production runs. Three minor discrepancies were identified and corrected (inlet turbulence intensity specification, reference pressure location, and particle-tracking integration step). Final setup was re-reviewed and approved. Post-processing scripts are version-controlled and unit-tested."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The hemolysis power-law model and turbulence closure are justified for the flow regime and device geometry through direct comparison with physics-resolving simulations or published independent validation studies covering the full COU operating envelope at MRL 5.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model combined with the Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law has an extensive publication record in centrifugal blood pump CFD, including several FDA-sponsored round-robin studies. The team's internal benchmarking against three independent experimental datasets from the literature demonstrates that the model form captures the dominant hemolysis mechanisms under design-point conditions. Expert panel review (five independent biofluid mechanics specialists) concluded that the selected model form represents current best practice for this device class. The Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification ensemble, which sampled power-law exponent and coefficient distributions derived from published calibration studies, produced 90th-percentile hemolysis predictions that remain below the clinical threshold, providing additional assurance that model-form uncertainty is bounded in a conservative direction. While a direct comparison against large-eddy simulation or DNS reference data at off-design operating points has not been completed within this assessment cycle, the convergence of expert judgment, published validation evidence, and the conservative UQ envelope is considered sufficient to support acceptance of the overall credibility package for regulatory submission."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material properties and boundary condition inputs characterized with stated uncertainty; sensitivity analysis identifies influential inputs and confirms UQ coverage.",
      "rationale": "Blood viscosity, density, and power-law hemolysis coefficients are characterized from published literature distributions and propagated through the Monte Carlo ensemble (10,000 samples, Latin hypercube sampling). One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis identifies power-law exponent and rotational speed as the two most influential inputs. Both are assigned appropriate distribution widths consistent with inter-laboratory variability in the published calibration literature."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental sample size sufficient to characterize measurement variability; inter-run repeatability reported for hemolysis index measurements.",
      "rationale": "The FDA NHLBI dataset includes n=6 replicate hemolysis measurements per operating point across two independent test rigs. Inter-run coefficient of variation is below 8% at all five operating points. Sample size is consistent with ASTM F1841 guidance for hemolysis testing of blood-contacting devices. Measurement uncertainty is incorporated into the validation comparison metrics."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters (geometry, fluid properties, operating conditions) demonstrated to be equivalent to experimental test conditions within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "CAD geometry used in simulation was derived from the FDA-released STL file for the generic centrifugal pump. Dimensional verification confirms maximum deviation of 0.03 mm from nominal. Fluid properties in simulation match the reported bovine blood properties from the experimental dataset within measurement uncertainty. Operating point equivalency is confirmed by matching flow rate and rotational speed to within 0.5% of experimental set points."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-acceptance-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-review-board",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Following review of all thirteen credibility factors, the assessment team concludes that the CFD hemolysis prediction model meets the overall credibility requirements for regulatory submission under the VAD COU. Twelve of thirteen factors achieve their required credibility levels. The Model Form factor is assessed at level 2 against a required level of 3; however, the team judges that the combination of extensive published validation evidence for the SST k-omega and Giersiepen-Wurzinger model pairing, the favorable expert panel consensus from five independent specialists, and the conservative Monte Carlo uncertainty envelope — which demonstrates that 90th-percentile hemolysis predictions remain below the clinical threshold — collectively provide sufficient confidence in the predictive adequacy of the model form for this device and operating envelope. The team further notes that the level-2 achievement reflects a documentation gap (absence of LES/DNS reference comparison) rather than a demonstrated predictive failure; all quantitative validation metrics are within acceptance bounds. On balance, the weight of evidence supports acceptance of the credibility package, and the decision is recorded as Accepted pending completion of the LES comparison study as a post-market commitment.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
